    Same in the office          
    and the basement.           

02:26.012 --> 02:28.480
All right, everybody, let's try 
    and stay ready for 'em.     

02:28.548 --> 02:29.782
                Ten-four, Sammy.

02:29.849 --> 02:30.949
     Listen to you people.      

02:31.017 --> 02:32.951
        Every Halloween,        
you go on this ridiculous alert,

02:33.019 --> 02:35.187
        waiting for Gary        
 and the deadbeats from his bar 

02:35.255 --> 02:36.922
to come over here and scare you.

02:36.990 --> 02:38.724
I mean,                         
you're tense all day,           

02:38.792 --> 02:39.925
        you're checking         
    under the tables,           

02:39.993 --> 02:41.493
    you're even afraid          
     to go to the bathroom.     

02:41.561 --> 02:43.062
      Well, we go upstairs      
         to Melville's.         

02:44.164 --> 02:47.166
          Hey, it's once a year.

02:47.233 --> 02:49.501
 Well, I think you guys should  
just call it off; I mean,       

02:49.569 --> 02:50.803
                    I think it's
                really childish.

02:50.870 --> 02:52.137
Excuse me? Childish?            

02:52.238 --> 02:53.739
Sweetheart, this is             

02:53.807 --> 02:55.441
bar versus bar.                 

02:55.508 --> 02:58.210
We will use any weapon          
available to us.                

02:58.278 --> 03:01.013
        Water balloons, stink   
         bombs, whoopee cushions

03:01.081 --> 03:02.514
and fake vomit.                 

03:02.582 --> 03:04.516
                Yes, fake vomit.

03:05.885 --> 03:09.588
Now, how childish is it?        

03:09.656 --> 03:11.690
          Remember last year, we
          sent Cliffy over there

03:11.758 --> 03:13.525
             wearing nothing but
              a pair of Speedos?

03:13.593 --> 03:14.727
         (all laughing,         
          snickering)           

03:16.262 --> 03:18.330
Those people were               
screaming like banshees.        

03:18.398 --> 03:19.999
(laughs)                        
             Yeah.              

03:20.066 --> 03:22.368
    Well, I was making          
         a scary face.          

03:25.872 --> 03:26.872
      Hey, Sam, I'm back.       

03:26.940 --> 03:27.973
                          CARLA:
                    Oh, look,   

03:28.041 --> 03:29.641
a bumpkin with a pumpkin.       

03:29.709 --> 03:32.478
Yeah, it's from                 
my building's roof garden.      

03:32.545 --> 03:34.880
     I entered this contest     
the local merchants are throwing

03:34.948 --> 03:36.548
 for the best jack-o'-lantern.  

03:36.616 --> 03:38.050
                  First prize is

03:38.118 --> 03:40.953
        a cruise around         
         Boston Harbor.         

03:41.021 --> 03:43.055
They say it's three hours       
      you'll never forget.      

03:43.123 --> 03:45.891
  Especially if it's low tide.  

03:45.959 --> 03:47.226
LILITH:                         
Woody,                          

03:47.293 --> 03:48.594
 it's hard to believe you grew  

03:48.661 --> 03:50.195
     such a hardy specimen      
          in the city.          

03:50.296 --> 03:53.198
Well, yeah, the trick           
is to give it lots of care.     

03:53.266 --> 03:54.500
                I took a seed   

03:54.567 --> 03:56.702
from last year's pumpkin,       
planted it,                     

03:56.770 --> 03:58.671
and watched over it             
like a daddy.                   

03:58.738 --> 04:00.973
I'd even lie in bed             
at night thinking,              

04:01.041 --> 04:02.908
"I wonder how                   
the pumpkin's doing."           

04:04.477 --> 04:07.980
Pruned it, weeded it,           
checked the soil.               

04:08.048 --> 04:10.416
I even talked to it.            

04:10.483 --> 04:12.518
    I think they like that.     

04:13.553 --> 04:15.054
        Aah!                    

04:16.488 --> 04:18.423
Farm boys love their Halloween! 

04:23.496 --> 04:24.863
I always hated this night.      

04:24.931 --> 04:26.865
                            Why?
Well, when I was a kid,         

04:26.933 --> 04:28.467
my folks used                   
to move around so much          

04:28.535 --> 04:30.269
that they never really got      
to know the neighbors,          

04:30.337 --> 04:31.704
so they didn't trust them.      

04:31.771 --> 04:34.006
So when all the other little    
kids had their costumes on,     

04:34.074 --> 04:35.240
and they were                   
trick-or-treating,              

04:35.308 --> 04:37.543
all I was allowed to do         
was stand at our front door     

04:37.610 --> 04:38.711
and pass out candies.           

04:38.778 --> 04:40.779
I could hardly wait             
till I was an adult,            

04:40.847 --> 04:42.314
so I could enjoy Halloween,     

04:42.382 --> 04:46.218
you know, and not spend all     
my time serving everybody else. 

04:46.286 --> 04:48.454
             Ah. That's too bad.

04:48.521 --> 04:50.456
            Could you pass those
            pretzels, please?   

04:51.758 --> 04:53.692
        (moaning):              
             Darn!              

04:58.198 --> 05:00.132
          I sympathize          
    with Rebecca's parents.     

05:00.200 --> 05:02.267
I, for one, will not            
allow my child                  

05:02.335 --> 05:05.404
to go trick-or-treating through 
the dangerous city streets.     

05:05.472 --> 05:06.739
        What luck!              

05:06.806 --> 05:09.008
I got the last Spider-Man       
     costume for Frederick!     

05:10.143 --> 05:12.077
                And look what he
            can use for webs.   

05:18.551 --> 05:20.419
Frasier, we need                
to have a discussion.           

05:22.222 --> 05:24.623
        Oh. no, don't tell me   

05:24.691 --> 05:27.593
                you have a thing
         against Halloween, too.

05:27.660 --> 05:30.396
I don't have a thing            
against Halloween.              

05:30.463 --> 05:31.964
I just don't                    
want my child                   

05:32.065 --> 05:33.932
panhandling door-to-door        

05:34.034 --> 05:35.834
accepting non-nutritious snacks 

05:35.902 --> 05:38.337
from strangers,                 
dressed in a silly costume.     

05:38.405 --> 05:41.173
                But, darling,   
              that <i>is</i> Halloween.

05:41.241 --> 05:43.042
    Oh.                         

05:43.109 --> 05:46.245
Well, then I guess              
I do have a thing against it.   

05:46.312 --> 05:47.579
         I got an idea.         

05:47.647 --> 05:49.214
      Why don't you bring       
  the little fella by the bar?  

05:49.282 --> 05:50.816
    We can, you know,           
  set up candy here and stuff.  

05:50.884 --> 05:52.017
    It'll be fun.               

05:52.085 --> 05:54.787
Well, I suppose                 

05:54.854 --> 05:57.456
if it's an environment          
which we know and trust,        

05:57.524 --> 05:58.991
that would be all right.        

05:59.059 --> 06:01.026
                I am not serving
        the little punk, Sam.   

06:01.094 --> 06:02.695
        I know.                 

06:02.762 --> 06:03.962
It's all right.                 

06:04.030 --> 06:05.297
Do me a favor.                  

06:05.365 --> 06:06.799
Will you take this over         
to Table Ten?                   

06:06.866 --> 06:08.801
                  Sure...       

06:09.869 --> 06:11.603
              All righty.       

