Yeah, a group of 19th century   
artists and writers             

11:38.765 --> 11:42.401
who held an almost-childlike    
submission to nature.           

11:42.469 --> 11:43.502
That's very good, Cliff.        

11:43.570 --> 11:45.137
How would you ever              
come to know that?              

11:45.238 --> 11:47.439
Ah, I came across it            
at the library.                 

11:47.507 --> 11:49.041
                     Yeah, going
            through art books   

11:49.109 --> 11:52.244
        looking for paintings   
            of naked babes, huh?

11:52.312 --> 11:54.413
Really liked 'em                
fat back then, didn't they?     

11:56.449 --> 11:58.050
        Freddy is, of course,   

11:58.118 --> 12:00.419
            bedecked in the garb
      of superhero crime fighter

12:00.487 --> 12:02.421
          Spider-Man.           

12:04.090 --> 12:05.791
            LILITH:             
         Interestingly,         

12:05.859 --> 12:08.594
Spider-Man acquired             
his supernatural powers         

12:08.661 --> 12:10.696
from the bite                   
of a radioactive spider.        

12:10.797 --> 12:11.964
I tried to explain              

12:12.032 --> 12:13.332
to Frederick what would         
happen if one were              

12:13.533 --> 12:15.501
really bitten                   
by a radioactive spider,        

12:15.568 --> 12:16.835
but he just cried.              

12:18.672 --> 12:20.272
                Okay, Fred, time
             for trick or treat.

12:20.340 --> 12:21.340
        Trick or treat, lady.   

12:21.441 --> 12:22.675
          Here we go.           

12:22.742 --> 12:25.277
Oh, thank you.                  
Thank you.                      

12:25.345 --> 12:27.546
  Hey, mister, trick or treat.  

12:27.614 --> 12:29.014
Thank you very much.            

12:29.082 --> 12:30.883
Oh, look.                       

12:30.984 --> 12:32.951
            I'd like to tell you
        something, young man.   

12:33.019 --> 12:35.320
I don't know if you realize how 
lucky you are that your parents 

12:35.388 --> 12:37.423
 let you partake in the better  
      things of childhood.      

12:37.490 --> 12:39.892
        You know, I never got   
              to trick or treat.

12:39.959 --> 12:41.627
          I always had          
     to hand out the candy.     

12:41.695 --> 12:43.796
 Nobody ever gave me any candy. 

12:48.335 --> 12:50.803
          Look at that...       

12:50.870 --> 12:52.071
    Good boy, Freddy.           

12:52.172 --> 12:54.039
                  Thank you.    

12:54.107 --> 12:56.675
That's the first time anybody   
          ever gave me anything.

12:56.743 --> 12:58.711
        Thank you, Frederick.   

13:00.613 --> 13:02.314
                 The kid's got a
             bagful of Snickers,

13:02.382 --> 13:04.149
                 and he gives me
                  a Tootsie Pop.

13:06.252 --> 13:08.587
             Oh, boy, do we have
            a surprise for Gary.

13:08.688 --> 13:10.322
SAM:                            
Those physics guys              

13:10.390 --> 13:12.491
set up the whole thing;         
the hologram's incredible.      

13:12.559 --> 13:14.560
      What macabre specter      
    will they be projecting?    

13:14.627 --> 13:18.564
    Carla's disembodied head    
     floating over the bar.     

13:18.665 --> 13:20.265
      (muttering approval)      

13:20.333 --> 13:21.767
    Scary, huh, Norm?           
                        Yeah.   

13:21.835 --> 13:24.169
What would you do if you saw    
Carla's disembodied head        

13:24.237 --> 13:25.437
floating over the bar?          

13:25.505 --> 13:26.538
            What I always do.   

13:26.606 --> 13:28.007
         Call a cab and go home.

13:37.917 --> 13:39.385
          Oh, my Lord!          

13:39.452 --> 13:42.421
                        FRASIER:
        That would scare even   
        the most heartiest soul.

13:46.760 --> 13:48.360
    Oh...                       

13:48.428 --> 13:50.796
It's like being in              
a haunted house, isn't it?      

13:50.897 --> 13:53.399
A haunted house with free taps. 

13:54.934 --> 13:56.969
          I can't wait          
     for Gary to see this.      

13:57.037 --> 13:58.604
         He's gonna             
     really freak out.          

13:58.672 --> 14:00.873
        (chuckles)              

14:00.940 --> 14:02.474
Oh, here he is now.             

14:03.209 --> 14:04.643
                 Wow!           

14:04.711 --> 14:06.645
                He was so scared
                  he passed out.

14:06.713 --> 14:08.981
    Gee, I wonder what          
         we should do.          

14:09.082 --> 14:10.616
 Well, I think the responsible  
      thing to do would be      

14:10.684 --> 14:12.484
        to bring him to         
    and then, uh, run.          

14:12.552 --> 14:13.752
          (all laugh)           

14:14.988 --> 14:16.388
                      Hey, guys,

14:16.456 --> 14:18.657
            what if the blood   
        pressure stuff was true?

14:18.725 --> 14:20.092
              I mean, that could
                be dangerous.   

14:20.160 --> 14:21.427
Oh, come on,                    
give me a break.                

14:21.494 --> 14:22.628
He was faking.                  

14:22.696 --> 14:23.762
He's probably faking now.       

14:23.830 --> 14:25.431
Come on,                        
Gary, get up.                   

14:25.498 --> 14:26.699
I don't think he can, Sam.      

14:26.766 --> 14:28.500
     I don't feel a pulse.      

14:28.568 --> 14:30.602
      Oh, come on, you got      
         to be kidding.         

14:30.704 --> 14:32.338
            No, Sam.            

14:32.405 --> 14:33.706
          Gary's dead.          

14:43.583 --> 14:44.883
                Good morning!   

14:45.051 --> 14:46.151
                          CLIFF:
                Morning, Sam.   

14:46.219 --> 14:47.953
    It's a dark day.            

14:48.088 --> 14:49.588
          Oh, come on.          

14:49.656 --> 14:52.024
 You don't really believe that  
      Gary's dead, do you?      

14:52.092 --> 14:53.726
     (gasps):                   
     Do you?                    

14:55.061 --> 14:57.396
FRASIER:                        
I beg your pardon.              

14:57.464 --> 14:58.430
You were there.                 

14:58.498 --> 14:59.999
You saw with your own           
eyes what happened.             

15:00.066 --> 15:02.134
              This is Gary we're
                  talking about.

15:02.202 --> 15:03.369
            You can't trust him.

15:03.436 --> 15:04.636
                 Ever.          

15:04.704 --> 15:05.971
He's pulling a stunt.           

15:06.039 --> 15:07.139
             CARLA:             
         But the police         

15:07.207 --> 15:09.408
        and the coroner         
    confirmed it, Sam.          

15:09.476 --> 15:10.843
            Oh, no.             

15:10.910 --> 15:13.145
    No, he-he could've          
    hired them to trick us.     

15:13.279 --> 15:15.514
FRASIER:                        
Sam, I realize that             

15:15.615 --> 15:17.750
        Gary's death is         
     very traumatic for you     

15:17.817 --> 15:19.284
  and you're-you're obviously   
        in denial.              

15:19.352 --> 15:21.620
                No, I am not.   

15:23.156 --> 15:25.157
I can't believe you guys.       

15:25.225 --> 15:26.358
      I'll tell you what.       

15:26.426 --> 15:27.693
     I'll believe he's dead     

15:27.761 --> 15:29.028
as soon as they bury him.       

15:29.129 --> 15:32.097
        Gary's funeral's        
    at 2:00 this afternoon.     

15:33.566 --> 15:36.001
      This is a good one.       
      This is a good one.       

15:36.102 --> 15:38.137
              Life is so unfair.

15:39.572 --> 15:41.440
Yes, Woody, very often          
we feel that way                

15:41.508 --> 15:44.510
when someone close              
to us passes on.                

15:46.613 --> 15:49.181
        I'm talking about the   
        pumpkin carving contest.

15:50.417 --> 15:52.184
                  I mean, it had
                    to be fixed.

15:52.252 --> 15:53.519
                You should've   
                seen the winner.

15:53.586 --> 15:55.054
                     Teeth going
                every which way,

15:55.155 --> 15:58.023
    uneven eyes, stupid nose.   

15:58.091 --> 15:59.958
            You should have seen
             this kid's pumpkin.

16:03.063 --> 16:04.563
            Sam?                

16:04.664 --> 16:06.365
MATT:                           
Good morning.                   

16:06.466 --> 16:10.069
    I'm Matt, the bartender     
      from over at Gary's.      

16:10.136 --> 16:12.538
             Yeah?              

16:12.605 --> 16:14.540
  We're all kind of in shock,   
     but I thought I should     

16:14.607 --> 16:15.974
      come by and give you      
      something from Gary.      

16:16.042 --> 16:18.544
         This is good.          
        Watch this one.         

16:18.611 --> 16:21.480
         Oh, the bowling trophy.

16:21.548 --> 16:23.015
    Gary's prized possession.   

16:23.083 --> 16:25.017
MATT:                           
Gary came back                  

16:25.085 --> 16:27.119
from seeing you yesterday, Sam, 
and all he could talk about     

16:27.187 --> 16:28.787
was how concerned you were      
over his condition.             

16:28.855 --> 16:30.122
He was pretty                   
touched that                    

16:30.223 --> 16:31.957
after all this time             
of being rivals,                

16:32.025 --> 16:34.660
when it counted most,           
you really cared about him.     

16:42.836 --> 16:46.872
  That is so sweet and so sad.  

16:46.940 --> 16:49.375
          Oh, come on!          
        Give me a break!        

16:49.442 --> 16:52.177
The guy is probably hanging out 
     around here someplace.     

16:52.245 --> 16:53.812
      Hey, what're you up       
      at Melville's, Gary?      

16:53.880 --> 16:55.014
         Come on down!          

16:55.081 --> 16:56.281
        (chuckles)              

16:56.349 --> 16:58.951
Wow, you are                    
cold, man.                      

17:00.053 --> 17:01.653
      I was gonna ask you       
        for a job,              

17:01.721 --> 17:03.689
but pfft!-- forget it now.      

17:06.259 --> 17:07.358
        Now, he's good.         

17:07.426 --> 17:08.694
    He is really good.          

17:10.096 --> 17:11.696
                        REBECCA:
                Sam, stop it.   

17:11.765 --> 17:12.964
            The game is over.   

17:13.032 --> 17:14.733
         A man is dead.         

17:14.800 --> 17:17.036
     You know, it's getting     
a little bit embarrassing.      

17:17.103 --> 17:19.972
    It's time for you to face   
     the fact that Gary is dead.

17:20.040 --> 17:21.607
             That you had a hand
                in his death.   

17:21.675 --> 17:22.741
                     We all did.

17:22.809 --> 17:24.108
        That's the end of it.   

17:24.176 --> 17:26.145
Yeah, maybe you're right.       

17:26.212 --> 17:28.480
     All right, I admit it.     

17:28.548 --> 17:30.082
     Waah-waah, he's dead.      

17:30.150 --> 17:31.083
      (laughs)                  

17:31.151 --> 17:32.551
Come on, you guys.              

17:32.619 --> 17:34.420
Lookit, he's bluffing.          

17:34.487 --> 17:36.955
  I wonder how far he's really  
going to take this thing.       

17:38.291 --> 17:39.825
I'll be he's not even in there. 

17:43.630 --> 17:45.564
    Okay, so he's in there.     

17:50.570 --> 17:51.837
                I still think   
                it's a trick.   

17:51.905 --> 17:53.806
      If he wants to stay       
    in there and suffocate,     

17:53.873 --> 17:55.474
              it's fine with me;
            it's his funeral.   

17:55.542 --> 17:57.009
             Oh...              

17:57.110 --> 17:59.345
    Sam, we'd like you          
      to be a pallbearer.       

17:59.446 --> 18:01.313
         Well, why me?          

18:01.381 --> 18:02.781
          I mean, Gary hated me.

18:02.849 --> 18:05.050
It's a shame you never knew how 
  much he thought of you, Sam.  

18:05.118 --> 18:07.653
                He thrived on   
            your competition.   

18:07.721 --> 18:09.888
        You brought him life.   

18:09.956 --> 18:11.890
Then you took it away.          

18:13.460 --> 18:15.294
         I don't want to be     
        a pallbearer.           

18:15.362 --> 18:16.595
                        FRASIER:
                            Sam,

18:16.663 --> 18:18.997
                  it's the least
                you could do.   

18:24.037 --> 18:25.971
        Oh, I know what         
    he's going to do.           

18:26.039 --> 18:27.406
        All right,              
we're walking along here,       

18:27.474 --> 18:29.108
        all of a sudden,        
      the coffin opens up,      

18:29.175 --> 18:30.642
         he reaches out         
    and grabs my hand.          

18:30.710 --> 18:33.645
          Yeah, right.          
Ooh-ooh, I'm scared, yeah.      

18:33.713 --> 18:35.647
Come on, Gare, I got you.       
    Come on, open up.           

18:35.715 --> 18:37.483
    (knocks on coffin)          
Hello? Come on out, Gary.       

18:38.952 --> 18:40.953
(owl hooting in distance)       

18:54.234 --> 18:56.335
         Come on, Gary.         
        Enough's enough.        

18:56.403 --> 18:58.504
 It's getting chilly out here.  

18:58.571 --> 19:00.506
                          CLIFF:
                          Sammy?
              Hmm?              

19:00.573 --> 19:02.207
          Come on, the funeral's
            been over for hours.

19:02.275 --> 19:04.276
 No, no, you don't understand.  
  See, that's the whole thing   

19:04.344 --> 19:05.644
     about practical jokes,     
          it's timing.          

19:05.712 --> 19:07.646
  I know this; I've done this   
    a thousand times before.    

19:07.714 --> 19:09.448
        Matter of fact,         
if I don't miss my guess,       

19:09.516 --> 19:11.016
     he'll be coming out...     

19:11.084 --> 19:13.619
      right about... now.       

19:14.921 --> 19:16.121
        Right about now.        

19:17.323 --> 19:18.657
            Come on,            
    you're milking it, Gary!    

19:18.825 --> 19:20.092
    Get out of there!           

19:20.193 --> 19:22.361
                        FRASIER:
              I don't think he's
                coming out, Sam.

19:22.429 --> 19:24.630
    Yeah? Well, then I'm...     
      I'm digging him out.      

19:24.698 --> 19:26.765
         Come on, Gary.         
            Come on.            

19:26.833 --> 19:28.434
No, you don't understand.       
        This is a stunt.        

19:28.535 --> 19:29.835
      No, come on, you can      
    hear him laughing.          

19:29.903 --> 19:30.803
        He's laughing--         
          I hear you!           

19:30.870 --> 19:31.804
        You're laughing,        
          I know that!          

19:40.280 --> 19:42.247
     Okay, Gary, I'm back.      

19:42.315 --> 19:43.782
        You can come out        
    and scare me now.           

19:43.850 --> 19:46.185
        Shh-shh! Watch.         

19:46.252 --> 19:49.088
    Oh, Sam, he's not here.     

19:51.958 --> 19:53.892
            Oh, my God...       

19:56.262 --> 19:58.397
    What if he's really dead?   

19:58.465 --> 20:01.266
The thought has                 
occurred to me, Sam.            

20:05.372 --> 20:07.272
                 He's gone.     

20:07.340 --> 20:08.907
            He's really gone.   

20:08.975 --> 20:11.810
Gary had to go out              
of his way to prove it to you,  

20:11.878 --> 20:14.279
but, yes, Sam,                  
he's gone.                      

20:14.347 --> 20:18.150
     I feel like I've lost      
        my best friend.         

20:18.251 --> 20:19.985
             CARLA:             
    Having Gary around          

20:20.086 --> 20:22.121
              was, like, the one
            thing that always   

20:22.188 --> 20:24.923
            seemed to pull us   
            together as a group.

20:24.991 --> 20:28.327
Yeah. Gary really brought out   
the best in us, huh?            

20:28.428 --> 20:30.996
  No, Cliffie, he brought out   
        the worst in us.        

20:31.064 --> 20:32.464
    He will be missed.          

20:34.000 --> 20:36.001
      Boy, I'll tell you,       
I've done a lot of things       

20:36.069 --> 20:39.204
 that I regret, but I'll never  
be able to make up for this one.

20:39.272 --> 20:40.973
                    You know,   
            maybe it's time I   

20:41.107 --> 20:43.142
         stopped acting         
    like an overgrown child.    

20:43.209 --> 20:46.645
 I mean, a man is dead because  
  I did not have the maturity   

20:46.713 --> 20:47.846
     to know when to stop.      

20:47.947 --> 20:50.015
Never thought                   
I'd say this, but...            

20:50.083 --> 20:51.116
          I miss Gary.          

20:51.184 --> 20:53.118
 He's a... he's a true friend.  

20:54.354 --> 20:55.988
      That would have made      
      a better eulogy than      

20:56.056 --> 20:58.290
"Get out of there, Gary."       

21:04.631 --> 21:06.865
        I feel so empty.        

21:06.966 --> 21:08.834
            (crying)            

21:10.670 --> 21:12.504
                          WOODY:
                      Excuse me.

21:12.572 --> 21:14.306
    (continues crying)          

21:14.374 --> 21:15.974
SAM:                            
Woody, come,                    
come back here.                 

21:17.210 --> 21:19.178
      Oh, come on, Woody.       

21:19.245 --> 21:20.579
    God, it's all my fault.     

21:20.647 --> 21:22.581
    (Woody sobs loudly          
          in distance)          

21:24.084 --> 21:26.352
Hey, Woody, come on, man.       

21:26.453 --> 21:29.188
      You, you don't want to cry
        by yourself in there.   

21:29.289 --> 21:31.690
     Come on, come on, man.     

21:31.758 --> 21:33.759
Come on, listen,                
hey, hey, listen to me.         

21:33.827 --> 21:34.860
  Listen to me.                 

21:34.928 --> 21:36.362
We all feel bad.                

21:36.429 --> 21:37.396
    (crying continues)          

21:37.464 --> 21:38.530
                 Do you, Malone?

21:38.598 --> 21:40.432
                  Do you really?

21:40.500 --> 21:41.467
            (laughs)            

21:45.905 --> 21:47.406
        Trick or treat!         

21:51.177 --> 21:54.013
        You... you were         
     all in this together?      

21:54.080 --> 21:57.516
 Hey, the whole city of Boston  
    was in on this one, Sam.    

21:57.584 --> 22:00.419
    Come on, you're supposed    
    to be on my side.           

22:00.520 --> 22:03.022
    It was really funny, Sam.   

22:04.124 --> 22:05.190
        Yeah, but you're        

22:05.258 --> 22:06.759
my pal, man.                    
Come on!                        

22:06.826 --> 22:09.561
  It was really, really funny!  

22:09.629 --> 22:12.431
Sammy, I told you.              
I told you we wanted to be      

22:12.499 --> 22:14.566
on the winning end              
of a great scam.                

22:14.634 --> 22:15.701
That was a clue.                

22:15.769 --> 22:17.069
      Yeah, but you never       
          really gave           

22:17.137 --> 22:20.072
    that Chinese food thing     
        a chance.               

22:22.308 --> 22:24.710
     Hey, too bad you can't     
    get back at me, Malone,     

22:24.778 --> 22:26.345
but you're a big boy now.       

22:26.413 --> 22:30.182
 You don't want to play pretend 
 'cause people could get hurt.  

22:30.250 --> 22:32.351
            Whoops!             
This, I believe, is mine.       

22:32.419 --> 22:33.419
                            SAM:
                Oh, no, wait!   

22:33.520 --> 22:35.421
         Hey, the game          
    is not over, Gary!          

22:35.488 --> 22:36.955
     Hey, listen, I'm going     
    to find something           

22:37.057 --> 22:38.457
                to scare you.   
            I swear to God I am!

22:38.525 --> 22:40.192
            Here, use this, Sam.
Ooh, yeah, yeah, yeah.          

22:40.260 --> 22:42.594
         Bloody thumb!          
         Bloody thumb!          

22:42.662 --> 22:45.064
          Whoo! Whoo!           

